docs.text: martin scorsese's triumphant adaptation of edith wharton's the age of innocence is a stunning film for the quintessential new york filmmaker , the man who brought the streets of taxi driver and mean streets to life .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: it seems like an odd choice for scorsese to do a period piece in the early 1900's , but the fact that he pulls it off so brilliantly is a wonder , and a testament to the greatness of scorsese as a filmmaker .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: this is a gorgeous visual experience that it surely one of scorsese's finest .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: newland archer ( day-lewis ) is a prestigious lawyer who is engaged to may welland ( ryder ) , a somewhat empty and shallow new yorker , who belongs to a prestigious family and is quite beautiful .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the marriage is one which will unite two very prestigious families , in a society where nothing is more important than the opinions of others .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: on the day that archer is to announce his engagement to may , countess ellen olenska ( pfeiffer ) , cousin of may , walks into archer's life .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: archer is immediately captivated , and finds himself in love with ellen .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: archer is also bound by the limits of new york society , which is an intrusive as any other in the world .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: archer finds himself having a secret love affair in his mind with countess olenska , attempting to keep her in his mind while trying not to lose his social status .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the film's subject matter may seem alien to scorsese , but the theme is definitely not .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: it is a theme of forbidden romance , guilty pleasures , and the consequences causes because of those actions .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: there is a painstakingly flawed hero , and his choice between the life he wants , and the life he is destined for .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: in truth , it is a film about a society the audience doesn't know about , but wants to find out more , much like the society of goodfellas or even kundun .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the performances are absolutely breathtaking .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: day-lewis portrays more mental anguish in his face than one man should be forced to take .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: pfeiffer is marvelous as countess olenska , a mix of passion and beauty that the audience would die for as well .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: ryder is probably the gem of the group , for it is her quiet presence that overwhelms the plot , and slowly pushes day-lewis closer and closer to his eventual ending .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the supporting cast is also wonderful , with several characters so singular that they are indelible in one's memory .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: scorsese definitely has a passion for filmmaking .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: his lavish and sumptuous set design and marvelous recreation of new york is a wondrous sight .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: he literally transports the viewer to another world with incredible imagery .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: his script is also excellent , slow in buildup , with a rapid conclusion and a fantastic ending that has to be seen to be believed .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: it is difficult to make a period piece gripping : scorsese , however , does it beautifully .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the famous cameras of the legendary director are also everywhere .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: he is patient , but he films everything and anything remotely important .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the cameras sweep , pan , track , and do more than they've ever done , but they are so subtle , one doesn't realize he's watching all the scorsese hallmarks until a 2nd viewing .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the central tracking shot is probably longer and more complex than the famous goodfellas shot , but the viewer doesn't notice it , because we want to see more of this gorgeous world .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: there are a few deft touches of filmmaking that are simply outstanding , and joanne woodward' narration is exquisite .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: not a fast film like goodfellas , this shares more in common with kundun than anything else .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: and like kundun , this is a slow-starting film that truly shines , when given the chance to fully breathe and bloom in the end .
docs.label: positive
